{% extends "base.html.j2" %}
{% block title %}Environments · Realism Framework{% endblock %}
{% block content %}
<h1>Environments</h1>
<p>A preliminary evaluation of {{ envs|length }} cyber environments across the 11
realism dimensions. Select an environment for its coverage radar, its fit by objective,
and sources.</p>

<section class="findings">
<h2>What the evaluation shows</h2>
<p>Realism is use-case-relative: an environment can be well suited to one objective and
unsuitable for another. Two families emerge:
<strong>{{ family_counts.get("Real-software emulator", 0) }} real-software emulators</strong>
cover the technical, attacker-facing dimensions, while
<strong>{{ family_counts.get("Abstract simulator", 0) }} abstract simulators</strong>
cover topology and the agent interface but abstract the surrounding context.</p>
<p>The dimensions most often <em>absent</em> across these environments are
{{ least_covered|join(", ") }}, so objectives that depend on them are systematically
under-served. In this catalog, <strong>no environment yet supports</strong>
{{ unserved|join(", ") }}: the objectives that most need those context dimensions.</p>
</section>

<section class="categories">
<h2>Environment categories</h2>
<p>Beyond the two families, each environment carries an implementation tier, shown on its page:</p>
<dl>
  <dt>A (abstract simulator)</dt>
  <dd>Models the network symbolically, with no real hosts (no VMs or containers) and no real-time clock, so every subsystem is simulated.</dd>
  <dt>B (sim-to-real hybrid)</dt>
  <dd>Primarily simulated, but with a documented mode that runs on real hosts, such as an emulation mode or a demonstrated sim-to-real transfer.</dd>
  <dt>C (real-software emulator or range)</dt>
  <dd>Runs on real hosts, services, and operating systems by construction.</dd>
</dl>
<p>In this catalog the abstract simulators are all category A, and the real-software family splits into the hybrids (B) and the full emulators and ranges (C).</p>
</section>

